column168: On 11/03/08 at 00:14, CSXT personnel in the Kayne Avenue Rail Yard reported UTLX 200589, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide Aqueous Solution, leaking from the top of the tank car when moved in the rail yard. column168: Tractor Tank Trailer traveling South on I-95 Attleboro Ma. at 04:45 on 11/06/2008 was being passed by other vehicle (2001 Volvo Sedan) when operator of Volvo lost control of vehicle struck barrier and than came across all three (3) travel lanes striking TT and resulting in Unit Rollover on right side, came back to upright and came to final rest on left side, blocking entire roadway. Barrel suffered punctures in two (2) areas (right front side, right rear side) partial head collapse on right front which resulted in the loss of 3500 gallons of Jet A onto the roadway into storm drains and impacted a swall that runs parallel to roadway. Tanker was drilled at three (3) different locations and pumped off. Vac trucks were utilized to clean storm drains, booms and pads were deployed in impacted area to contain spilled product. Swall is 6/8 feet in width and 150/175 feet in length 50 feet south of the Read Street Overpass.
column169: Little can be said, our driver was doing his job in a safe, courteous manner when the reckless operation of vehicle 2, by operator 2 resulted in this event. Given the type of event it is my belief that the vessel performed beyond my expectations.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 11/08/08 at 09:45, personnel in the CSXT Skillman Yard in Hawesville KY reported discovered GATX 5954, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the rail car when moved. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified thru CHEMTREC (report # 20081108-0032). Summit Environmental, a CSXT contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the non-reclosing pressure relief device frangible disc ruptured. Summit personnel removed the 100 psi rated rupture disc and replaced it with a correct 165 psi rated rupture disc. The tank car was decontaminated and released to destination.          Note: A special switching move was made.    Note: AAR 7.1 form was not completed.     NARRI :  2 (5+5+0) * (2+0) = 40  Cause Code = 440
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 11/08/08 at 01:55, personnel in the CSXT Erwin TN yard discovered GATX 18051, a residue tank car of environmentally hazardous substances, liquid, NOS. (BIS (2-Ethylhexyl) Phthalate) leaking product from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated, the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (# 20081108-00010), and the state of Kentucky EMA was notified. A CSXT response contractor, HEPACO, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve handle was not secured and the packing gland on the valve stem was leaking. Hepaco personnel tightened the packing gland nut two to three turns to stop the leak. The leak was secured and the car released for transportation.      A special switching move was not required  An AAR 7.1 Form was not completed.       NARRI :  2 (4+1+0) * (2+0) = 20  Cause Code = 547
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Our driver loaded at the shipper and in the process of checking out of the shipper's facility, our trailer was discovered to be leaking slightly so the unit was moved inside a containment area.  When our driver performed a slosh test, product leaked out from underneath the vaccum breaker dome.  A mechanic was sent to the plant to repair the vaccuum breaker and found that the oring was missing.    The vaccuum breaker was repaired and the unit was allowed to head to its destination.
column169: Most of the issues we have with these vaccuum breakers is related to the o-ring either missing or being the wrong type.  We will continue to meet with all of our shop employees to re-enforce the importance of doing the job right, the first time, every time.  Part of our process includes changing all of the rubber o-rings to the teflon o-ring to prevent it from reacting to the chemicals and becoming distorted or swelling to the point that it breaks off.
column198: Enterprise Transportation Company a division of EPCO, INC.

column168: The freight was loaded by the shipper so this was considered a shipper load and count. The shipper did not properly secure the freight for transportation. This was picked up by ABF terminal 137 and sent directly to terminal 159 where the spill was discovered. A drum fell over and split in two places  . The consignee (same company as the shipper) went to the ABF terminal in Bakersfield, CA (terminal 159) and handled the clean up and the damaged drum.
column169: 137/VNT should be notified of the error and let them know that they must load lock/block and brace when picking up haz mat from the Nusil Technology plant in Carpinteria to avoid possible spills in the future.

column168: When unloading this order from the city unit directly after the pickup from the shipper, the dockman had found that this freight was loaded on the pallet without a sheet of cardboard to protect the product from the slats in the skid. The freight had shifted on the pallet during transit causing this   box to become crushed and fall between the slats on the pallet. It was found that only the box was wet that contained the product. there was no spillage to the trailer or to surrounding shipments. The dockman unloaded this box and restacked the pallet for safe transit. We held this box on the dock w  aiting for disposition from the shipper for possible return authority to be repackaged or to obtain a new box.
column169: Sales rep for this shipper has been advised of the problem we have with the shippers loading procedures. It has been recommended that cardboard always be placed on their pallets before stacking freight.

column168: On November 10, 2008 at approximately 1350 hours a Quality Carriers truck was receiving a load of Methyl alcohol at IMTT-Bayonne when a slight drip was noticed coming from the internal valve on the tanker trailer.  The operation was shut down and a 5 gallon pail was placed under the valve to contain the dripping product.  The truck was then moved to secured containment location and arrangements were made to have another truck brought to the area and transfer the product from the leaking trailer to the empty one.  The second trailer was then brought back to the loading rack and the operation resumed without further incident.  At the time of the incident it was determined that a defective internal valve on the tanker trailer caused the leak.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident.  The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the tanker truck and related components to prevent recurrences.

column168: Driver was unloading material using a roper product pump mounted on the rear of the   transport vehicle. Product temp was 150F and unloading normally. Driver states that the trailer was within appx 500 gallons of empty when the product transfer hose ruptured. Driver shut down the pump and closed the product valves on the trailer. The spilled material was contained and cleaned up by plant operator and driver.   The hose showed a hole about 10 inches from the end coupling at an area that would bend as the hose falls away from the trailer liquid discharge valve to the ground.  There was about an hour involved in the cleanup. driver teplaced the damaged hose and completed delivery. The ruptured hose was issued new to the driver one year ago and was only used several times a month prior to the incident.
column169: The carrier has a product hose testing proceedure in place and is investigating the cause of this incident. This was a relatively new hose that is designed for high temp products. Acording to the driver and the plant operator ther was nothing unusual about the unloading process.

column168: A BNSF road switch crew switching in the railyard reported a chemical odor emanating from UTLX 641170 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car). A small amount of liquid release was also observed from the top of UTLX 641170 during movement. Movement was stopped and no product release was observed when UTLX 641170 remained motionless, but the chemical odor persisted. UTLX 641170 was cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 641170 finding 2 of 8 of the manway securement bolts less than tool tight. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The intact manway seal numbered 0041755 was removed to check the product outage level and the manway gasket condition. The outage level was gauged and deemed appropriate. The manway gasket was intact and did not appear to be deficient. The responders replaced this manway gasket to ensure that a good seal was provided by the installation of a new Viton manway gasket. Afterwards, the manway was closed, properly secured and resealed with seal numbered 001358. The product spillage on the outer shell and a small amount found atop the ground ballast below was neutralized. An industrial odor-masking agent (OD 62) was sprayed upon the impacted area of the outer tank shell and the ground ballast to eliminate the chemical odor. UTLX 641170 was moved (agitated) at its location and no further product leakage was observed. Response was concluded by 0130 hrs. CST, 11/13/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Per supervisor report, driver was performing pump off delivery at the above location - Driver has to stop pumping due to unrelated activites taking place at the time of the pump off. The valve tothe tank that the driver was pumping into was closed. When the driver was given the "go ahead" to continue the pump off, the driver failed to ensure all valves were reopened prior to pumping. The driver activated the pump and pushed product against a closed valve. The pressure caused the hose to separate at the cupler resuling in a spill of red dyed dsl. The spill was contained and cleaned up by TAZ Environmental.
column169: Driver received a "Written Warning" QA and loss of Safety bonus.

column168: On November 7, 2008 at 11:30 AM, personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay Car Shop discovered GATX 61434, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, with a vapor leak from the top of the car. The car shop was evacuated and the Baltimore City Fire Department, the Maryland Department of Environment and the shipper (Delta Chemical) were notified. A CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager was dispatched to the scene and, with the State and Local responders, found that the Frangible Disk had crack in it allowing vapors to escape from the car. The CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager and Maryland Department of Environment personnel changed the frangible disk with an in-kind disc and the release stopped. The car was decontaminated and released for transportation.  NOTE: No special move was required  NOTE:  No AAR 7.1 form was required         Cause Code: 441  NARRI:  2 (4+5+0) X (2+0) = 36
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF road switch crew switching in the railyard reported UTLX 902979 (DOT 105J300W tank car) dripping product from the top fitting area of this tank car during movement. UTLX 902979 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting further inspection. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was called and inspected UTLX 902979. Intact seal number RH01 083009 was removed from the valve housing cover. The responder reported that the closed liquid line valve's packing retainer plate was loose and product was dripping from this valve's stem area. The two nuts on the opposite ends of the packing retainer plate were loose (1-1 1/2 turns loose) and once these were tool tightened at 0600 hrs. CST, 11/15/08 the product dripping ceased. Product spillage rapidly evaporated and no ground pooling was evident. New seal numbered BNSF HAZMAT 002473 was applied to the valve housing cover.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Our CHS repair facility in Janesville, WI. was venting off an anhydrous ammonia trailer, preparing it for repairs. Following standard procedures for this process (bubbling off trailer into a water tank that has charcoal filters installed), a motorist passing by the facility reported an ammonia smell and called the fire department. Upon arrival, the Milton, WI. fire department and the Rock County, WI. Sheriff's department discovered that there was no issue with our process. This incident was reported to the WI. Department of Natural Resources as well and the National Response Center as a matter of reference only.
column169: Ordered and installed new charcoal filters in water tank as a precaution only.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TILX 190478 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) in the railyard. TILX 190478 was isolated in the railyard. A BNSF responder immediately inspected TILX 190478. The responder found the BOV operating handle not pinned and not in the closed position. The bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) was tool tight, but a slow drip of product was observed emanating from around the BOC. The responder moved the BOV operating handle to the closed position and stabilized or pinned the handle. Afterwards, the product drips from the BOC ceased. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 0838 hrs. PST, 11/15/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: When the truck from Enterprise (Truck 20627, trailer IC248) was leaving the plant, it was noticed that there was a slight leak.  The product had come out of the vacuum breaker and leaked around the lid.  A small amount (approx a tablespoon) hit the ground. The loader secured the truck, put absorbant pads around the dome/breaker, and had the truck spotted on the loading pad. Enterprise called there trucking company to repair the vacuum breaker.
column169: Recommendation: Pressure/Vacuum test the trailer more often.

column168: During standard unloading process of LP Gas trailer, residents of nearby townhouses reported gas smell due to driver bleeding down unloading hose after delivery (standard procedure). Beford, NH. fire department and Bedford, NH. police department responded to townhouses. They called the local utility company to take gas readings in buildings. Utility company got reading of 2% which initiated evacuation. Fire department got a 0% reading. Found out that the utility company's meter had not been reset after last reading, causing a false reading of 2%. Residents were allowed back in building after this finding. They were evacutated for 15 minutes. The incident was called into the NRC as a matter of formality. Weather conditions and wind direction played a significant role in this incident.
column169: Did followup driver training on procedures for bleeding off hoses during specific weather conditions to ensure this type of incident does not reoccur.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While on the dock, one carton containing two (2) 1/2 liter bottles was crushed by the forklift.  Upon investigation it was discovered that one bottle was damaged.  Approximately 1/2 liter of free product was released and impacted the dock.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel performed the cleanup using goggles, rubber gloves and absorbent material.  The cleanup material, and damaged carton with entire contents were placed into a small salvage drum pending shipper instruction.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING AS A RESULT OF ONE OFTHE INNER METAL CANS DISCHARGING INSIDE THE BOX.  ONCE IT WAS DISCOVERED THE UNLABLED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE CONTAINED AN AEROSOL SHIPMENT, THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  I CONTACTED THE FAA REGION OFFICE AT 15:30 CST ON MONDAY, NOVEMBER 3, 2008 TO ADVISE THE OFFICE OF THE INCIDENT.  I FOLLOWED UP WITH FAA MIKE GIVENS ON WEDNESDAY 11-5, 2008 AND AGAIN ON FRIDAY 11-7-2008.  ONE OF HIS FAA AGENTS, JUDY REAGAN, WAS SCHEDULED TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. THE SHIPPER HAD EARLIER PROVIDED THE MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED, AND STATED THEY HAD THOUGHT THEY WERE SENDING IT BY GROUND SERVICE AND DID NOT REALIZE IT WAS FEDEX EXPRESS. THE SHIPMENT IS CONTINUING TO BE HELD, AND THE CONSIGNEE WILL BE CONTACTED AND ASKED TO PICK THE PACKAGE UP.   IF THEY REFUSE IT WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column168: A van trailer being parked at the 10 day storage yard was transported to the intended waste disposal facility.  The driver noticed a small amount of liquid had leaked from the drum to the trailer floor when opening the rear doors.  The response crew was notified, donned the appropriate PPE and using an absorbent material, cleaned up the leakage.  No material reached the ground, it was contained in the trailer, less than 1 quart had escaped.  The ring top of the drum was loose which caused the spill.  The drum was tightened, the absorbent material placed into a salvage drum and the load was offloaded at the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipper was notified to insure all drums are properly closed per drum manufacturers specifications.

column168: A van trailer parked at the 10 day storage yard was to be moved to the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon opening the rear doors, it was discovered that approximately 1 gallon of liquid had leaked onto the floor of the trailer from a drum.  No material had leaked onto the ground.  The response crew was notified, donned the appropriate PPE and began cleanup. One drum was found to have a pinhole leak in the bottom.  The drum was overpacked into a salvage drum and the trailer was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material.  The trailer was then unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the shipment was accepted for transportation, the containers were inspected and no evidence of leaking or damage was identified.  Drivers will contiue to inspect each container as it is loaded and will take appropriate corrective actions should a container be observed that has questionable structural integrity or is leaking.

column168: Pale was originally loaded on top of a decking table from ABF terminal 120. It was not properly secured to the decking table and it fell through and dented can enough to cause opening. resulting in leakage/spill.~~~NOTE: The terminal did not document the package identification markings for this repo  rt.
column169: Do not load haz mat on top of decking tables unless properly secured to the decking table and the table is properly secured within the trailer.

column168: ABF driver John Drozdowski, upon his arrival at the ABF Tomah, Wisconsin facility noticed that there was some product loss on the top of a closed top drum that was Hazardous. It is unclear how the packaging failed, as no one tried to unload the drum with a drum cart, and the loading terminal loaded   these drums with a fork lift. The ABF driver called our Safety and Security department, who advised the ABF driver that an Emergency response team would do the clean up. HAZ-MAT ONE responded to the call, and determined that there was a small puncture near the top ring of the drum. Product loss was   limited to 2 cups and was put in one small drum along with PPE and other clean up debris. This puncture may have been caused by a drum grabber, but not for certain.
column169: Check all future shipments from this shipper to ensure that the product they are shipping have no small indentations that might compromise the integrity of the container. Instruct all drivers and dock personnel to be extremely careful when loading (or when observing the loading by shipper), that no   damage is done to containers during loading, unloading or during transit.

column168: Driver arrived to location at 1800 hrs on 11/22/08 to drop 2001 gross gallons of Unleaded 87 octane gasoline.  According to the drivers statement he finished dropping driver replaced hoses and fitting back to the vehicle.  Entered the station to retrieve station veedor reading and after completeing ending stick reading product came back out the drop tube.      Fire department was called and situation was contained and clean-up crew was summoned to arrive within the hour.  Clean-up was complete approximately three hours after the incident occured.
column169: Have requested customer maintenance to check pressure capes on vapor pipes to insure they are not clogged.  Director of Safety has supervised the next 2 deliveries without any problems.  We will continue to monitor this station to determine what occured to prevent any future incidents of this nature.

column168: DURING DRIVER TRAINING THE WEEK PRIOR TO SPILL, DELIVERY TICKET FOR 1000 GALLON TANK WAS GIVEN TO DRIVER.  WHEN DRIVER AND TRAINER GOT TO THE HOUSE, THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO DETERMINE THE PROPER HOUSE OR LOCATION OF THE TANK FILL FROM THE DIRECTIONS ONTHE TICKET.  THE TRAINER MADE THE DECISION NOT TO DELIVER UNTIL HE HAD BETTER INFORMATION.                                                         FRIDAY MORNING THE TRAINER CALLED THE CARETAKER WHO DIRECTED HIM TO CALL THE PROPERTY OWNER.  SPOKE WITH PROPERTY OWNER AND WAS TOLD GRIFFITH WAS AT THE RIGHT HOUSE AND THE FILL WAS AROUND THE REAR OF THE GARAGE FROM THE DRIVEWAY WHICH WOULD PUT IT ON THE RIGHT SIDE FACING FROM ROUTE 13.  THESE INSTRUCTIONS MATCHED THE FILL LOCATION LISTED IN THE ACCOUNT INFORMATION.    DRIVER WAS SENT TO THE LOCATION MONDAY. DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE MAIN HOUSE AND LOCATED THE FILL ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HOUSE WHERE GRIFFITH WAS TOLD IT WOULD BE TO CONFIRM INSTRUCTIONS, THE DRIVER CALLED HIS TRAINER AND DESCRIBED THE FILL AND VENT, AND MENTIONED THAT THE FILL PIPE HAD A SCULLY FILL ON IT. THIS BY ITSELF LANELED THE FILL AS AN OL TANK FILL PIPE. THE TRAINER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER PROCEED WITH THE FILL, AND HE DELIVERED 656G TO THE 1000G TANK.    THE TRAINER WAS CONCERNED OVER THE AMOUNT OF FUEL DELIVERED AND DECIDED TO CALL THE CARE TAKER TO VERIFY THE ABNORMAL AMOUNT. TRAINER AND CARE TAKER DISCOVERED GRIFFITH HAD BEEN DIRECTED TO FILL AT THE WRONG FILL PORTS.    THE PROPERTY WAS INSPECTED TUESDAY MORNING. REMEDIATION BEGAN IMMEDIATELY AND THE PROCESS CONTINUES.

A van trailer contaiing hazardous waste was enroute from the shippers location to the intended waste management facility.  DUring the course of the trip, the vehicle made a routine stop at Clean Harbors in transit storage facility for the purpose of transferring the shipment to an alternate vehicle for continuing transportation.  During the transfer operation, a fork-lift operator struck 2 55 gallon containers with the forks of the lift when he attempted to stop the lift.  this resulted in the puncture of 2 containers.  As a result of htis incident, approximatley 100 gallons of material escaped onto the floor of the van trailer and the secondary containment truck parking location.  The facility immdiatley activated it's internal emergency response plan and steps were taken to overpack the damaged containers and absorbe all free liquids.  ALl debris collected from the area and recontainerized for disposal and were sent for dispoal to the intended waste managemetn facility.  In addition, the vehicle was decontaminated and put back into service.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the fork-lift operator will be retrained on the proper operation of mechanical handling devices.  We also believe that environmental factors contributed to the incident.  At the time of the incident it was raining and it is believed that the fork-lift failed to stop due to wet pavement.  Weather conditions and understanding of potential hazards will be adressed with this individual as well.

column168: A BNSF switch crew switching railcars in the railyard reported a petroleum gas odor emanating from CRPX 986035 (DOT 112J340W tank car). CRPX 986035 was cordoned off in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical responder inspected CRPX 986035 and no leak source was found, but a slight product odor was detectable. The local F.D. arrived and also inspected CRPX 986035 and other railcars nearby. The F.D. found no leaks and detected no product odor. Afterwards, the BNSF switch crew resumed switching and shortly thereafter reported the same petroleum gas odor. Again the area around CRPX 986035 was cordoned off. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected CRPX 986035 and determined that the odor source emanated at the sample valve port. The consignee (Chevron) was contacted and their response team arrived at 0515 hrs. PST, 11/03/08 to inspect and repair CRPX 986035. The consignee response team tightened the sample line valve stem packing retainer one full turn by 0650 hrs. PST, but a slightly detectable product odor persisted. It was assumed that the sample valve packing was deficient and CRPX 986035 was delivered to Chevron for unloading by 0740 hrs. PST, 11/03/08.   At 0750 hrs. PST on 11/08/08, CRPX 986035 (now a residue shipment billed by Chevron) was reported emanating a residue product odor at the BNSF Barstow, CA railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected CRPX 986035 and found a rag wrapped around the sample line pipe. The sample line pipe was cold to the touch indicating that residue product vapor was escaping up through the sample line pipe. The responder applied a sealant compound into the pipe nipple's threaded area and into the threads of the valve body. The sealant compound was worked into the threads by turning the valve body 1/4 turn. Afterwards, the residue product odor was no longer detectable. Home shop disposition was requested for CRPX 986035 and it was forwarded accordingly.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On November 16th, 2008 at 10:59, personnel in the CSXT Niagara Yard discovered GATX 62558, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid (UN 1789) with vapors emitting from the top of the tank car. GATX 62558 was isolated and the consignee, Occidental Chemical was called by local yard supervision. Chemtrec was notified (Report #20081116-00010). Occidental Chemical personnel responded and found the frangible disc had activated and there was no noticeable release of product on top of the tank car. The disc was replaced, and the car released for transport.      An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not required for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32

The Airgas Merchant Gases driver and co-driver were returning to the terminal in Canton, OH after a delivery in Allen, KY. The driver ran off of the interstate crashing into a guardrail and a bridge abutment causing substantial damage to the undercarriage of the truck and a rollover. At some point a fuel tank was ruptured and a fire was ignited. The tractor was totally destroyed and the fire impinged upon the cargo tank. The vapor pressure within the tank was enough to overcome the relief devices installed on the unit. As a result the integrity of the tank was compromised and cause the pressure to release in the area of the intense heat exposure, just behind the king pin. The release was mostly vapor and was of a short duration according to the fire chief on the scene. As Nitrogen is the main component of air there was no mitigation required.
column169: We as an organization have increased our efforts at drivers awareness to the affects of fatigue (suspected root cause). The hazardous material and cargo tank had no apparent impact on initiating the accident.

column168: A BNSF yard employee reported a chemical odor in the railyard and BNSF supervisory personnel searched the railyard for an odor source. No chemical odor was noticed and no railcars were observed leaking any commodity. Later, another chemical odor complaint surfaced. BNSF responders along with contract responders were dispatched to the Slaton railyard. During the detailed inspection of the railcars in the yard, the responders reported finding UTLX 642768 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a chemical odor via the manway closure. No release of liquid commodity was evident. The manway gasket was out of position (bulged outward and protruded over the manway nozzle lip) which prevented a good gasket seal. After the manway cover was opened, a small cut (3-4 inches in length) was visible running lengthwise across a portion of this gasket. Responders replaced this gasket with a new suitable manway gasket and resecured the manway cover. Afterwards, no further chemical odor was detected.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering fuel to a customer location. The station's veeder root has been down and the station has no tank charts. The driver was instructed prior to delivery to use the Oilmans chart book and driver was told that the station has 12k tanks. The driver however, used the wrong tank charts and while unloading fuel he noticed the product leaking out of the tank. The driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 5-8 gallons came out of the top of the tank. All product was contained on concrete and no product reached drains or soil. The spill was cleaned up by the driver and on site personnel. Our regional safety supervisor inspected the site to ensure satisfactory cleanup.
column169: Driver had been counseled on the tank charts at this location just prior to delivery, therefore driver was suspended for 1 day and was retrained on company policy, to include contacting his dispatch if there were any doubts or questions he had prior to attempting delivery. Driver also couseled on unloading procedure.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering fuel to a customer location. While unloading fuel into compartment 4, the driver noticed fuel coming out of another tank. Driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 15-20 liquid gallons had leaked and allthough some was contained, there was a tarp on the ground from nearby construction and some of the fuel that leaked onto the tarp was released into a nearby storm drain. It was determined that the cause of the spill was that tank 3 and 4 were labeled wrong on the ground. QT (customer) site personnel conducted the investigation and came to this conclusion. QT accepted full responsibility for the cleanup. The mis-labeling of the tanks caused the driver to fill tank 3 instead of tank 4 as he had thought. SWS and Chattahoochie environmental responded to the spill.
column169: Quick Trip Facilitied Support also responded to the site, the team changes the labels on the tanks to avoid any future problems. The remote drops were also properly labeled and verified.

A BNSF responder immediately inspected TILX 302890's top fittings under the valve housing cover. The responder reported finding the vapor valve slightly open and emanating a vapor hiss. column168: During highway transportation of a hazardous waste shipment between Carolina P.R. and Mayagüez, P.R.; while passing through the municipality of Isabela, P.R., the transportation vehicle was cut off by another motor vehicle.  The incident required the truck driver to implement an emergency stop in order to avoid an accident.  The sudden stop caused movement of the truck’s cargo. In particular several 5-gallon plastic pails, that had been sheen-wrapped together, shifted forward.  One of the pails was punctured by a nail from the palette directly in front of it, that had apparently been damaged during the sudden stop.  The puncture hole was approximately .25 inches in length.  This information was not immediately known to the driver because the cargo container had security seals.  After the incident the driver stopped and reviewed the outside of the container and did not observe any leaks.  He continued his trip and upon arriving at the Lilly del Caribe, Inc. plant in Mayagüez, reported the incident.  Upon opening the cargo container, the punctured pail was discovered lying on its side with approximately one gallon of liquid still inside.  The truck bed was also found to be wet and some material started to drip from the truck bed onto the roadbed during the truck inspection at the Lilly gate.  No sign of spillage was found outside Lilly property.    The pail was immediately removed in order to control the release.  The truck bed and affected roadbed was dried with absorbent material and the truckbed was also mopped and decontaminated.  Since the Mayagüez facility is a RCRA Treatment, Storage, and Disposal (TSD) facility all liquid waste collected was treated on-site.  Solid waste was disposed off according to applicable RCRA Hazardous Waste regulations.
column169: As part of the incident investigation it was determined that improved sheen-wrapping techniques needed to be implemented to assure not only that pails are wrapped together but that they are firmly fastened to their respective palettes.   More specific instructions will be given to personnel on how to better prepare shipments for transportation. The practice of assuring that only palettes in good condition are used for shipments was already in place so the palette involved in the puncturing is assumed to have been damaged during the braking incident.    The use of metal grating palettes with side walls is being considered for future shipments of plastic pails.  This should prevent pails from tipping over or moving during future shipments.  In addition the use of stronger wooden or metal palettes is being considered for all waste shipments.

column168: A BNSF carman inspecting railcars in the railyard reported a chemical odor emanating from these railcars. The area was cordoned off and all BNSF employees working nearby were moved to the north end of the railyard. BNSF and contract responders were summoned to investigate, determine the odor source and take corrective measures to eliminate the odor. Inspections revealed ECUX 374027 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) on an adjacent track emanating a product odor. Seal XOM 010385 was removed from the valve's protective housing cover to inspect valve securement. Responders found ECUX 374027's vapor valve (VV) 1/2 turn loose on its threaded connection into a one inch reducer pipe. Also, the vacuum relief valve (VRV) was two turns loose at its threaded connection into the tank car. After the VV and VRV were tool tightened, no further product odor was evident. Valve housing cover was resealed with seal numbered 0729010. No liquid product was released. Response was concluded by 1410 hrs. CST, 11/20/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported PROX 16769 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) in the railyard leaking product from its top fitting area. PROX 16769 was cordoned off in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected PROX 16769 and reported that internal pressure build up within the tank car was forcing product up the liquid eduction piping which sprayed out at the closure cap connection. Pressure was relieved and the responder removed the closure cap. The cap was cleaned; Teflon tape applied to the threaded area and the cap was reapplied to a tool tight condition. Spillages on the shell and ground impact area were neutralized with an application of baking soda. PROX 16769 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for continued monitoring.  On the morning of 11/19/08, inspection of PROX 16769 revealed a slight leak of product at the liquid eduction closure cap. The closure cap was removed and cleaned again. Teflon paste was applied to the threaded area of the cap. The cap was then reapplied and tool tightened. Additional monitoring resulted in no further product leakage observed from the closure cap and PROX 16769 was released to proceed to its destination at Noon MST on 11/20/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Defective Component or Device
column168: A BNSF mechanical rail car inspector reported a chemical/sulphur odor emanating from UTLX 650101 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 650101. The responder reported finding a portion of the manway nozzle gasket pinched and bulging out from under the manway cover. After the manway cover was opened to reposition the gasket alignment, the responder noted that the gasket itself was cracked and torn in two locations along the circumference of the gasket. The responder surmised that deterioration of the gasket resulted in the gasket damage rather than the misalignment. The responder applied a new suitable gasket and properly resecured the manway cover. BNSF seal numbered 06157532 was applied at the manway. After the manway cover was secured, no further residue product odor was detectable. No liquid product was released from this incident. The responder also noted that the valve housing cover was not pinned (locked) and sealed. The responder applied the valve cover locking hook and threaded BNSF seal numbered 06157539 to secure the valve housing cover. Response was concluded by 1020 hrs. PST, 11/30/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column25: Hyundai Intermodal Inc. by Halliburton Energy Services
column168: Hyundai's assigned driver notified BNSF intermodal hub personnel that intermodal container HDMU 255377 for Indonesian export via sailing vessel was leaking liquid product in the intermodal parking area. BNSF external inspection of HDMU 255377 revealed liquid leakage at the rear doorways and right sidewall and nose area of this container. HDMU 255377 was carefully moved to the containment and transfer dock area and placed over visqueen sheeting with a bermed perimeter. Hyundai arranged for a contractor to remediate spillage; and determine and eliminate the leak source.  The contractor reported that four 55 gallon steel closed head drums (UN Specification 1A1/Y1.2/200/08/USA/M4634) were damaged and leaking. It appeared that the damaged drums had impact damage and stress fractures that originated from loading activities with no evidence of load shift or rough handling during rail transportation. It was also noted that 23 other drums in this load incurred impact dents and drum distortion from excessively tight drum pallet banding. All non-damaged drums were transferred to another suitable container for continuation of their export movement. The contractor overpacked the leaking drums and remediated all non-evaporated spillage. The overpacked drums which included non-leaking damaged drums that were deemed unfit for overseas shipment were earmarked to be returned to the originating loader/shipper Halliburton Energy Services in Houston, TX.
column169: Ensure shipper's loading processes of non-bulk hazardous material shipments are fully implemented and validated to avoid damage to the packaging.

Instead of being routed to our shop for maintenance, it was inadvertently put on another load.  The trailer was loaded from the top and the internal was secure so the problem wasn't noticed until it was being unloaded.  The trailer has since had the internal valve, gaskets, external valve and bleeder valve replaced. The outside vendor that we had do the annual inspection was notified of all the problems.

column169: BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP OR LIDS ON DRUMS. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: Vehicle was stopped for a DOT roadside inspection Level II - Walk around.  During the inspection a 15 gallon drum was discovered to be leaking.  The drum had sustained a crack on the upper shoulder when the load was being secured.  The drum contained EZ SPOT (Isobutanol Solution).  As the vehicle was in motion, the contents of the drum sloshed up against where the crack was in the container causing a small amount to run down the side of the drum.  No material left the vehicle.  Louisiana State Police notified Halliburton of the incident and that notification to the Hazmat reporting hotline need to be made.  This call was performed and report number 08-07464 was issued.  Additionally report was made to Bossier Local Emergency Response Planning Commission.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was unloading gas at a customer location. After unloading regular gasoline the driver dropped the hose prior to walking the hose to ensure there was no fuel in it. The dropped hose leaked approximately 5-10 gallons of fuel. The spill was completely contained on concrete and no product reached soil or drains. The spill was completely cleaned up by the driver and the site was inspected within 2 hours by a regional safety supervisor and noted that there was no evidence of a spill and all concrete was dry.
column169: Driver was in too much of a hurry to unload properly and was counseled on proper unloading procedures and warned he needed to slow down and walk hoses down before disconnecting. An incident prevention observation was done on driver.

column168: A Univar driver was making a delivery of methyl ethyl ketone bulk to a customer in Forest City, NC. One of the customers employees was helping our driver get everything hooked up and inadvertently the inlet and outlet hoses got switched on the pump due to the driver connected the hoses at the tank truck and at the customers storage tank prior to hooking up at either of the pump connections and as the driver started the pump to begin the product transfer our tanker overflowed as material was pumped from the customers tank to our tank truck. The pump and valves were immediately shut down stopping the flow of product. The truck and tanker was in a contained area and all material was immediately cleaned up with absorbents. All in all about 10 gals of material spilled and was immediately cleaned up.
column169: I had discussion with driver about checking to be sure hoses are connected properly to his truck pump also made sure that the inlet and outlet was marked on the trucks pump as they were supposed to be and found that was ok, also advised driver to hook up one hose at a time and complete the hook up from tanker to truck and truck to storage tank so that the loose hoses can not be mixed up at the pump connections. This information will also be relayed to all bulk employees.

column168: This is still under investigation.  It looks like an incompatible material was loaded into the tank, product delivered and tank cleaned.  Then tank was loaded with another product and leaked at the seam due to deterioration.
column169: Operating procedures are being revised to prevent this in the future.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering gas to a customer location. While unloading the driver noticed product bubbling and knocking the stomp down off. This caused approximately 8 gallons of fuel to spill onto the concrete. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product and no product reached soil or drains. The driver then took stick readings and veeder root readings and both showed that the tank could hold another 250 gallons. The driver notified the attendant and manager at the site. He utilized oil dry to absorb the spill. The stomp down was checked and was determined to be in good working order, further investigation revealed that the flapper was closing early and caused the hose to jump and knock off the fitting. The site manager replace the faulty flapper and accepted responsibility for the incident.
column169: The fauly part on the tank, the excess fill flapper/valve was replaced. This was ensured to be done before unloading at this location again.

column168: A non dot specification closed bulk bin (dump trailer) was enroute from the shipper's location to a fully licensed waste management facility to dispose of a shipment of incinerator ash.  At the time of loading, the ash was loaded at a temperature above ambient temperture which we suspect allowed condensation to form on the exterior of the liner.  During the course of transportation, it was discovered that a small amount (less than 1 gallon or 8 solid pounds)leaked from the rear of the dump trailer.  It is believed that the condensation formed as the material cooled collected on the exterior of the liner allowing the liquid (believed to be water) to release from a small pinole in the dum trailer body.  Upon identification of the situation, a third party contractor was secured to travel to the scene to absorbe all free liquids and secure the truck for continued transportation.  ALl clean-up debris was placed in the dump trailer and disposed of at the intended waste management facility.    It is our belief that the materia released was simply condensation but due to the fact that the dump trailer contained a hazardous waste, it was reported as a hazardous materials incident.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the loading facility has been informed of the incident nad have been requested to inspecte each shipment prior to offering for transportation to insure that any condensation is removed and the presence of any free liquid is addressed.

column168: A vehicle containing a manifested shipment of hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's lcoation to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the vehicle made a routine stop at a Clean Harbor's facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities of hazardous waste onto a single vehicle.  During the transfer operation, it was discovered that a 55 gallon non bulk package developed a pin hole leak allowing approximately 1 gallon of material to escape onto the floor of the vehicle.  Facility personnel immediatley halted the transfer operation and activated the faciliy's emergency resposne plan.  Steps were taken to place the leaking container into a suitable salvage container.  In addition a suitable absorbent material was applied to the material released and this clean-up debris was placed in the salvage drum along with the compromized container.  Once the clean-up was completed, the salvage drum was secured and was placed on the trailer for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation from the shipper, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  The driver has been instructed to continue inspecting each container prior to accepting for transportation and take those steps necessary should a damaged or compromised container be identified.

column168: This incident occurred on 11-26-08 at approximately 1315 hours when driver Justin Bomar (Foster Fuels driver) was delivering Diesel Fuel to A. Byron Smith Oil bulk plant.  When driver Bomar arrived, no A. Byron Smith Oil personnel were present.  Driver Bomar attempted to unload the product without the assistance of bulk plant personnel.  After connecting all of the piping Bomar began the unloading process.  After a short period of time Bomar noticed product escaping from the cargo tank overflow valve(vapor line), Bomar immediately shut down the unloading process.  The spillage ran down a alley road surface onto a concrete empty parking lot.  Bomar failed to close a discharged valve from the bulk piping which caused product to be pumped from the bulk storage into the cargo tank and overflow.  Bomar did not realize the discharged valve from the bulk piping was open until he had shut the unloading procedure down.  Estimated time of product release is 3-5 minutes.  Product released did not reach any type of public or natural waterway.
column169: Driver Bomar is trained in the loading/unloading procedures at Foster Fuels, and has unloaded at this facility in the past.  In this particular delivery, Bomar attempted to unload without the assistance of bulk plant personnel.  Foster Fuels will not longer permit unloading/loading at this facility without the assistance of bulk personnel.  Foster Fuels would recommend bulk plants to post unloading/loading procedures, mark all piping, and unloading/loading not be premitted without the assistance of company personnel.  No type of equipment failure is attributed to this incident.  Foster Fuels will continue to provide training in the furture to all of its HM employees.  This incident has been made a part of Justin Bomar's employment record at Foster Fuels Inc.

column168: Driver spotted Vehicle at consignee's designated unloading area, then proceeded to connect cargo hose to receiving line. Once driver was given the authorization to unload, he proceeded to apply compressed air to the cargo tank and the transfer of product began. During this stage of the process product began leaking from the lower rear area of the cargo tank. Compressed air feed was isolated and residual pressure released. An external suction pump was applied to remove the remaining product. Spillage was contained within secondary containment and an environmental response contractor was called out to recover product and cleanup the containment area.
column169: Trailer lining was repaired on 02/27/2008 and cargo tank returned to service. Failure is currently under investigation. Recommend the use of conductivity testing during the loading process as this would have alerted us to the fact that lining failure was imminent.

column168: When driver got to consignee with the loaded cargo tank, he was told that product is usually pumped off.  Driver said his work assignment said to use air pressure.  Customer said that was fine.  Customer had a 1500 gallon tank that was empty.  Driver was delivering 1300 gallons.  That would allow for 200 gallon headspace in the tank.  Driver  had the air line half closed to keep psi between 15-25.  When the discharge line went empty and the hose jumped, driver was right there and immediately closed the discharge valve on the cargo tank. The cap on the customer tank raised up and sprayed product on the side of the cement block building.  Driver said it was a 16" cap that locks on with only 1 turn. Product also sprayed out of the vent on the side of the tank. Driver and plant employee were unsure how much spilled.  Driver said less that 50 gallons which is probably an overestimate.
column169: Not sure if using air pressure was an issue, cap on tank not properly secured or maybe air vent to tank was plugged allowing pressure to build up?   The customer doesn't seem to have an issue when the product is pumped so future loads should be pumped.

column168: TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE, THE INFORMATION IN THIS REPORT IS COMPLETE AS WE ARE AWAITING A FINAL POLICE REPORT AND AUTOPSY RESULTS.  WE HAVE DATA FROM OUR NAVTRAK SYSTEM STATING THE VEHICLE CAME TO A HALT AT 3:16 AM CENTRAL TIME (4:16 AM EASTERN).  POLICE NOTED TO HAVE RECEIVED AN ACCIDENT CALL AT 4:20 AM EASTERN TIME.  THE POLICE WERE DISPATCHED AT 4:23:37 AN AND RESPONDED AT 4:23: 56 AM.  THEY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 4:35:42 AM AND WERE OFF THE CALL AT 7:58 AM COMPLETELY.  THEY SHUT DOWN THE HIGHWAY TO CLEAR THE VEHICLES AT 4:35 AM AND OFF CALL FOR        RECONSTRUCTION AT 7:20 AM.  THE POLICE DID NOT SEE OUR INCIDENT NOTIFICATION STICKERS OR EMERGENCY CONTACT INFORMATION DUE TO HEAD-ON COLLISION CAUSING SEVERE DAMAGE TO THE VEHICLE.  THE RAM PACKAGE WAS SECURE IN THE TRUNK OF THE VEHICLE (CHEVROLET COBALT 4 DOOR).  THE POLICE PHONED THE RSP RESPONDER WHO ARRIVED ON SITE TO EVALUATE THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMPLETELY INTACT WITH NO LOSS OF RAM.  OUR SITE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT BY RSO RESPONDER (BOB ANGER) AT 5:45 AM CENTRAL TIME AND THE SITE RSO INFORMED ME PERSONALLY.  WE DISPATCHED ANOTHER DRIVER TO RETRIEVE THE RAM PACKAGE AND RETURN IT TO OUR SITE IN ILLINOIS IN THE AFTERNOON.  I INFORMED OUR PRESIDENT OF THE INCIDENT.  WE PROCEEDED TO INFORM APPROPRIATE REGULATORY AGENCIES AND OTHER PARTIES AND OTHERS IN A TIMELY MANNER.  AT 8:30 AM I PHONED DAREN PARRERO IN ILLINOIS AT IEMA OF THE INCIDENT AND JAMES CAMERON AT THE NRC.  WE CONTACTED THE POLICE IN BOONE COUNTY, IN THE SAME DAY.
column169: PACKAGES WERE INTACT AND SECURED AND NO CHANGES WERE DEEMED NECESSARY TO ENSURE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SECURITY AND SAFETY.  PRESENTATION WAS GIVEN VIA WEB-EX TO RE-EMPHASIZE OUR COMMITMENT TO DRIVER SAFETY.  WE WILL CONTINUE TO MONITOR THE TRANSIT OF VEHICLES VIA NAVTRAK GPS SYSTEM.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman performing railcar inspections in the railyard reported AAR C113 type covered hopper INTX 7039 leaking product from its A-end bottom hopper outlet. A BNSF environmental contractor reported product escaped from metal corrosion splits/cracks at the weld seam at the top of the outlet chute above the A-end hopper outlet. The cracks were on the outlet chute facing outside and the side facing the B-end of the railcar. The remaining two bottom outlets were intact and not leaking any product. The contractor shoveled product piled on the ground into super sacks. Four sacks were used to clean spillage. Sacks contained a mixture of product, soil and ballast rock and they were earmarked for appropriate disposal. BNSF mechanical personnel applied construction adhesive into the cracks to allow INTX 7039 to continue to the nearby consignee to be unloaded without further leakage.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated including package integrity of the rail equipment to be used to transport hazardous material.

A bucket was put under it to contain the spill until the load could be transferred to another cargo tank.  A towing company and emergency response team assisted.  Fire and police stood by.
column169: Our safety manager has initiated various programs to stress with the drivers the importance of entering highway ramps at well below the posted speed.  It includes phone conferences with the newer drivers.

column168: On November 28, 2008 at 11:47, personnel in the CSXT rail yard in Waycross, GA discovered GATX 6296, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2008-11-28-00052). SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the liquid eduction ball valve was open slightly and the valve plug was not installed. Contractor personnel closed the valve, installed the valve plug tool tight and applied soda ash to neutralize the released acid. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.  Cause Code: 311  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: Preventable Rollover - Driver was allowing another truck to pass on four lane divided highway and got to close to shoulder of road causing L/R trailer tires to ride off into ditch pulling the whole unit with it. Driver tried to steer truck out of ditch and when he did truck rolled over on it's side. Rollover caused a 4222 gallon gasoline spill.  Soil pollution, but no clean-water act violation.  Tractor & Trailer likely totalled.    Action Environmental & WEL Incorporated contacted for clean up.
column169: Using more caution when allowing other vehicles to pass would have prevented this accident. The rollover & spill will be discused in next month's safety meeting as a reminder to use caution at all times.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO A WET PACKAGE AT DOOR 193 IN THE BLUE AREA. WEARING ALL MY PROPER PPE AND UTILIZING MY DECISION TREE/ RESPONSE SHEETS, I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY.  I THEN TOOK IT TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: Improper blocking and bracing was the cause of the spill.  The skid of paint was stacked on top of another skid of paint, with another skid of paint stacked on top of it, with nothing but a piece of plywood used as dunnage for blocking.  On the other side of the plywood was a smaller pallet and about 1 ft. of empty space. While in transit the top skid of paint shifted over and was leaning on the edge of the paint that was spilled.  The spilled was caused by the above pallet leaning over placing its weight on a single can of paint in the box below.  The side of the can of paint buckled under the pressure breaking the seal of the lid causing approx. 4 ounces of the paint to leak out and onto the trailer floor.  The can was leaking for approx. 3 hours (drive time from Dallas, TX to Shreveport, LA).
column169: Additional blocking and bracing could have prevented this incident form occurring.  The responsible parties could use some additional training on blocking and bracing freight properly.

column168: A BNSF mechanical railcar inspector reported that inbound inspection of VCSX 147 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the train yard revealed product drips emanating from under the A-end tank near the body bolster. Further inspection of VCSX 147 by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder determined that the tank shell was compromised at the aforementioned location and therefore necessitated product transfer. Product drips impacting the ground evaporated. VCSX 147 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for immediate product transfer. The product in VCSX 147 was transferred into tank trucks without further incident by 0430 hrs. PST, 11/29/08. Afterwards, VCSX 147 was cleaned and purged of hazardous material. On 12/18/2008 movement approval FRA-08120429 was issued to forward VCSX 147 to an approved repair facility for appropriate repairs.   VCSX 147's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.

column168: The truck had a 550 gallon tote carrying 350 gallons of hypochlorite solutions strapped in with a bottom outlet valve connected to a pump facing the back of the truck. A 2 wheeled dolly that was strapped to the wall broke loose and rolled into and cracked the PVC nipple going into the outlet valve. The tote started leaking out the floor of the truck and left a trail on the highway and into the parking lot of the high school where the truck was delivering to. The driver was unaware of the leak till he pulled into the parking lot of the school. He was followed into the lot by a police car. They immediately called the local fire department and the local has mat response team. They shut down the highway as a precautionary measure. The school was closed that day due to it being Veterans Day so there were no students there. There was a staff of 10 at the school which was evacuated even though it was leaking a small amount in the parking lot away from the school. It started raining while this was happening. 55 gallon drums were placed under the truck to catch the remaining hypochlorite solution leaking out while waiting for SET Environmental, Inc. to me in and clean up the back of the truck. They also hauled away the hypochlorite solutions that had been caught in the 55 gallon drum. The truck was released when SET was done cleaning up the back of it.

column168: On Wednesday, November 19, 2008, at 1215 hours CST, Ms. Stephanie Tudors, Claims Adjuster from Covenant Transport’s Group Risk Management/Claims Department (CTG) contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc (A•C•T) Nationwide Emergency Response Manager Mr. Gary L. Weiss to request assistance for a hazardous material spill of Dimethylaminoethanol (DMAE).  Tractor-trailer # 10941 was reported to be traveling northbound on I-81 at mile marker 59 left the roadway and traveled through a line of trees and hit a unoccupied barn.  As a result of the accident and the abrupt stop, the cargo in the trailer was propelled forward.  The trailer broke open spilling 14 55-gallon drums DMAE onto the ground.  The remaining drums in the trailer were damaged and dislodged throughout the trailer.  A review of the Bill of Lading showed the tractor-trailer was carrying 80 55-gallon drums of DMAE, each weighing 720 kilograms. DMAE is listed as UN 2051, Class 8.3 Packaging Group II.  It’s a clear, colorless liquid with a strong ammonia-like odor.  DMAE’s primary hazard is being a corrosive agent and secondary hazard is its flammability. The flash point is 32 degrees Celsius, has a vapor pressure of 0.89 at 22 degrees Celsius and is completely solubility in water. The National Fire Protection Association 704 marking system lists Health Hazard Rating of 3, and a Flammability Hazard Rating of 2.    Upon arrival at the site, our response team determined that the Kingsport Fire Department (KFD) had evacuated nearby homes due to the concerns over anyone coming in contact with the DMAE vapors.  Approximately 15 residents were temporarily evacuated due to this incident.  After the KFD completed air monitoring, the evacuated residents were allowed back at approximately 1630 hours CST.      Fourteen (14) drums were outside the trailer and leaking, with 67 drums still inside the damaged trailer.  All the drums were propelled forwarded during the accident; a basic visual inspection reveled that the majority of the drums were damaged.  The KFD had uprighted the drums outside of the trailer to prevent any further leaking.  A decontamination station was established by the KFD for all responders.    Mr. Weiss and our response team developed a plan of action to cleanup the site.  A drum staging area would be established and lined with poly sheeting.  All drums would be moved to the staging area to be overpacked.  This would require cutting the trailer open to gain access to the drums inside the trailer.  Once this was completed, soil samples would be collected to determined if any soil would be required to be excavated. Any remaining diesel fuel in the tractor’s saddletanks would also be removed.    Mr. Weiss contacted Mr. David Anderson of BASF, the shipper who confirmed that Level B Personnel Protective Equipment would be required.  This would consist of butyl rubber suits and self-contained breathing apparatus.  Our cleanup plan of action was reviewed with Mr. Anderson who approved

column168: ROBERT COLLIOUD, VP WAS CONTACTED BY A REPRENTATIVE OF THE DEP THAT STATED HE WAS DRIVING BEHIND OUR VEHICLE, PLATE #AL551W,AND STATED THAT HE OBSERVED LEAKING LIQUID DRIPPING OUT OF BEHIND THE BOTTOM OF THE REAR GATE DOOR ONTO THE REAR MUD FLAPS AND ONTO THE HIGHWAY. MR. COLLIOUD ADVISED THE INDIVIDUAL THALL ALL OF OUR DUMP TRUCKS ARE EQUIPPED WITH TURNBUCKLES. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE DRIVER, VIA CELL, AND ASKED IF THE DIRVER HAD ACTIVATED HIS TURNBUCKLES. THE DRIVER STATED HE DID ACTIVATE HIS SIDE TURNBUCKLES BUT FAILED TO ACTIVATE THE REAR. THIS DRIVER WAS ADVISED TO IMMEDIATELY ACTIVATE THE REAR TURNBUCKLES TO ENSURE NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WOULD OCCUR. HE THEN PROCEDED TO HIS UNLOAD DESTINATION.
column169: DUE TO THIS INCIDENT ETGI HAS TAKEN THE FOLLOWING STEPS TO ENSURE THIS TYPE OF FAILURE DOES NOT OCCUR AGAIN. THIS SPECIFIC DRIVER WAS IMMEDIATELY REPRIMANDED AND A LETTER OF DICIPLINARY ACITON WAS PLACED IN HIS FILE. HE FAILED TO ACTIVATE ALL OF HIS TURNBUCKLES.  WE HAD PLACED 5X8 WHITE DECALS WITH RED LETTERS ON THE DASH-BOARD OF EACH DUMP TRUCK THAT READS "GATE TURNBUCKLES ON/OFF" WE HAVE ALSO ADDED A SECTION TO OUR DRIVER MANUAL THAT STATES THE TURNBUCKLES MUST BE USED AT ALL TIMES WHEN LOADED. DRIVER FAILURE TO ACTIVATE THE TURNBUCKLES WILL RESULT IN IMMEDIATE DISCIPLINARY ACTION THAT MAY INCLUDE TERMINATION.

column168: An MEl tractor trailer had an accident at mile marker 50 south bound on Interstate 1-75. The trailer was partially loaded and load locks were in place to stabilize the load. After going onto the shoulder and down a heavily wooded embankment, the load of drums and buckets shifted and lost approximately 30 gallons of product (liquid).   This accident occurred on a newly paved section of 1-75. The truck slid off the road after the trailer Jack knifed on a slick rainy road. The truck traveled through the forested median knocking down some trees in its path. The tractor was mangled and tree limbs punctured the trailer. When It came to a stop, the diesel saddle bags were ripped off and some drums and buckets were knocked over inside the trailer. Approximately 30 gallons of product from the containers were spilled in the trailer. Diesel was spilled on the ground.   A Hazmat crew from MEl mobilized immediately. Upon arrival on the scene they dressed in appropriate P.P. E. and entered the trailer. They applied a clay based absorbent to the liquid In the trailer. Equipped with the MSDS and manifests and aware of the substances Involved In the wreck, they instructed the Government E.R. personnel of the properties of the waste. Once the truck was moved, the Hazmat crew excavated the soil where the diesel spilled. The following day the crew returned and restored the property with topsoil and seed.   The soil was tested and disposed of at a class C landfill. The residue in the truck was put in drums and sent to A.E.S. for disposal.
column169: The rainy conditions, coupled with a light load on new pavement caused this accident. The driver had a stellar record of 23 years without an accident. He was not speeding.   As a result of the incident we plan to have morning weather bulletins and instructions to all our drivers. We will advice and evaluate the need to reduce speed for the road conditions. We will postpone loads more readily when weather conditions could make road conditions treacherous.

column168: Intermodal container MSKU 260442 was reported leaking from the container doorway in the BNSF intermodal parking lot. (MSKU 260442 was a China import shipment that BNSF received for rail movement at the Port of LA that recently arrived on a BNSF train.) Absorbent material was placed on the ground to capture dripping product. BNSF contract responders inspected MSKU 260442 for the leak source, finding double stacked 320 gallon IBC's inside without any plywood sheet separators applied between the upper and lower IBC's. One top stacked IBC toward the container nose damaged the top of the IBC below it. Apparently the weight of the top IBC collapsed the metal cage surrounding the lower IBC which punctured the IBC's rigid poly bladder allowing product to escape. The remaining product within the damaged IBC was transferred into another suitable IBC. Afterwards, the empty damaged IBC was dismantled and placed into a recovery drum for future appropriate disposal. Several non-damaged IBC's were transferred into another container to eliminate the double stacking arrangement. The spillage inside MSKU 260442 was cleaned.

column168: An Accident Investigation was completed on November 24, 2008 and results are as follows:The driver was traveling East on CR1940 at approx 6:30 P.M. which is almost completely dark at this time.He just left a sharp northward curve and proceeded back eastward in a straight path slightly going uphill.The roadway in this area was very narrow and measured about 8' from center line to shoulder drop off. The shoulder drop off was estimated at a (1.5' paved) and 3-4' from roadway to ground surface, at a steep downward angle. The tractor/trailer traveled uphill and appeared to just fall off the edge of roadway and asfuel weight shifted it pulled the vehicle into the shoulder starting from trailer to tractor, and landing on itstop side. It appeared this was caused by the depth of the shoulder itself and the width of the actual travelsurface of the roadway.Driver was pulled to safety by unknown passer-by. With tractor/trailer on its top, fuel and heat ignited the cab (unknown source), and proceeded to burn the tractor/trailer, and fuel contents (approx. 5,000 Gallons) +2,000 gallons released into soil).

UPON LEAVING LOCATION ONTO OIL FIELD ROAD, DRIVER MADE A HARD RIGHT TURN.  THE ROADWAY GAVE WAY AND FELL OUT FROM UNDER THE RIGHT TRAILER TIRES CAUSING THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR TO ROLL ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  THE LIQUID SUNGA CAUSED THE DOME LID TO VENT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 BBL (21 GALLONS) OF CRUDE OIL.
column169: BECAUSE OF BLM RESTRICTIONS, MANY OIL FIELD ROADS ARE TO NARROW.  BLM IN MANY CASES WILL NOT ALLOW ENOUGH RIGHT OF WAY TO CONSTRUCT A SAFE ROAD BED.  THAT WAS THE CASE HERE. AFTER THE ROLL-OVER, BLM DID ALLOW THAT CORNER TO BE WIDENED.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY LESS THAN 0.880 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT AMMONIA.
column168: On Tuesday, November 25, 2008 I received a phone call from the plant manager of our Indianola facility that they had rolled an anhydrous ammonia tank on the way to a customer. after determining that it had broken off the liquid withdrawal valve, the pressure gauge had torn the acme threads off of the liquid fill valve. The plant manager on the seen said the there was some product escaping from the pressure gauge opening and that they were going to try and plug that opening. I then called and notified the IDNR of the incident at 4:50 pm. At this time the amount of product had not been determined.   Throughout the evening hours of November 25, 2008 I was in constant communication with Ted Peterson of the IDNR. At 6:30 pm on November 25, 2008, Agriland FS, Inc. General Manager had arrived on scene to help determine a way of moving the tank off of the gravel road. At 7:28 pm, it had been determined to go ahead and call the National Response Center to report a possible release of anhydrous ammonia that would exceed the reportable quantity of 100 lbs. The report number from National Response is 891013.  The weather conditions had become extremely calm with some humidity and would no longer allow the Agriland FS, Inc employees to get close enough to the tank to do anymore work as the vapor was just hanging in the air. At 8:21 pm on November 25, 2008, I then called the Warren County Emergency Management Coordinator for assistance. At that time Mahala Cox (Warren Co. Emergency Management Coordinator) called in the fire department to hel with the situation. The fire department then requested the HAZMAT team from Des Moines. I then notified Ted Peterson (IDNR) that the Warren Co Emergency Management Coordinator had been notified and that HAZMAT had been called at approximately 8:51 pm.  Ted Peterson (IDNR) called me back at 11:33 pm to let me know that he had been in contact with the HAZMAT team to help with suggestions and wanted a phone number of a person on scene that might have better reception, since he lost contact. I provided Ted Peterson with the contact that I had been communicating with.  John Knobloch, Agriland FS, Inc General Manager, called me at 1:13 am on November 26, 2008 to inform me that Mahala Cox (Warren Co Emergency Management Coordinator) and the HAZMAT team decided to barricade the gravel road and abandon the scene for the evening, since there was no air movement and not much vapor escaping at that time. this would allow employees of Agriland FS, Inc. to return that morning to attempt to recover the product during daylight hours and safer conditions.  i arrived on scene at 9:23 am on November 26, 2008 and met with Mahala Cox. At this time we did not see any product being released. At 10:00 am the other Agriland FS, Inc. employee showed up on scene to help determine the best way to move the nurse tank and recover the product.  The employees then determined that we could slide the tank with a wrecker and then pick the tank up in the ups

column168: Our CTMV was traveling West on N.E. Fields Rd. coming out of a 90-degree curve; a dump truck was traveling East on N.E. Fields Rd.; the dump truck was across the center line; our vehicle moved right to the point that it was off the roadway.  The right rear of our vehicle struck a large boulder shifting the rear end from its mounted position.  As a result of the impact a small propane vapor line was broken releasing approximately 1 gallon of propane vapor into the atmosphere.  The vehicle was towed to our facility to assess needed repairs.  *NOTE: The road closure was not the direct result of the Propane vapor dispersion. The road was closed to make access for recovery equipment to tow the vehicle from the scene.

column168: ON 11-13-08 A DRIVER WAS EN-ROUTE TO DELIVER 150# CHLORINE CYLINDERS.  WHILE HE WAS EN-ROUTE HE PULLED INTO A NO FACILITY REST AREA, LOCATED ON 1-4 AND MILE MARKER 127, AND PERFORMED A ROUTINE VEHICLE CHECK.  DURING THIS CHECK, THE DRIVER REPORTED SMELLING A FAINT CHLORINE ODOR THAT SEEMED TO BE GETTING WORST.  THE DRIVER STATE THAT THE SMELL WAS COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CYLINDER AROUND THE VALVE AREA.  911 WAS CALLED AND THE VOLUSIA COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AN APPLIED AN EMERGENCY KIT.  THE EMERGENCY KIT DID NOT WORK SO, THE HAZMAT TEAM INSERTED THE CYLINDER INTO A RECOVERY VESSEL.
column169: WE HAVE REVIEWED OUR TESTING, PACKAGING, AND LOADING PROCEDURES AND HAVE FOUND THAT OUR PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED.  THE TESTING RECORDS OF THE CYLINDER SHOW THE CYLINDER TO BE WITHIN TOLERANCE.  THE CONTAINER WAS FILLED AND STORED IN A HIGH FOOT TRAFFIC AREA FOR 3 DAYS WITHOUT ANY INDICATIONS OF ANY ISSUES.  THE TRUCK LOADER DID NOT DISCOVER ANY  ISSUES WHILE LOADING THE CYLINDER EARLIER THAT MORNING.  THE DRIVER DID NOT DISCOVER ANY ISSUES REGARDING THIS CYLINDER WHILE HE WAS PERFORMING HIS PRE TRIP INSPECTION.  THE DRIVER DID NOT DISCOVER ANY ISSUES WHILE OFF-LOADING AT A PREVIOUS DELIVERY.  THIS APPEARS TO BE AN ISOLATED INCIDENT.

column168: Operator was applying anhydrous ammonia with a tool bar trailed by a nurse tank.  The steel tubing that connects the front and rear axles of the nurse tank failed and the front axel was pulled out from under the nurse tank.  The front of the nurse tank trailer dropped to the ground shearing off the mainfold valve fitting releasing anhydrous ammonia to the atmosphere.  The release was stopped by the operator who closed a valve on the top of the tank.
column169: The undercarriage manufacturer has changed the design of the trailer due to reports of several other failures of the same kind.  This design change was not communicated tot he customers that were still using the old design.    Any kind of NH3 or LP equipment updates should be communicated to all the customers still using the old design.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CARRYING 11 SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE IBC'S, ONE NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IBC, AND TWO EMPTY CORROSIVE DRUMS RAN OFF OF ROAD CAUSING TRUCK TO ROLL ON ITS SIDE.  UPON IMPACT, THE 11 IBC'S WENT THROUGH THE CEILING OF THE TRAILER STRIKING A ROCK LANDSCAPING WALL CAUSING IBC'S TO CRACK AND RELEASE PRODUCT.  ESTIMATED DURATION OF RELEASE IS 20 MINUTES.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, AND HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AT SCENE AND EVACUATED A FAMILY WHO LIVES IN THE HOUSE WHERE CRASH OCCURRED.  CARRIER'S RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AND ALSO CONTRACTED WITH AN ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM TO CLEAN UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND RESTORE AREA.    CLARIFICATION FOR QUESTION 34 - THE DRIVER WAS INJURED IN THE CRASH.  TWO BYSTANDERS WHO HELPED THE INJURED DRIVER VOLUNTARILY CHECKED THEMSELVES INTO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION AND WERE RELEASED.  NEITHER PERSON EXPERIENCED ANY INJURY AS A RESULT OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.
column169: ADDITIONAL DRIVING TRAINING IS A RECOMMENDATION TO HELP PREVENT RECURRENCE.
